re, England":"Willenhall, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1231–":"circa 1231–Overleden","1227–Male":"1227–Overleden","1243–Female":"1243–Overleden","1262–Female":"1262–Overleden","1264–Male":"1264–Overleden","1266–Female":"1266–Overleden","1268–Female":"1268–Overleden","1231–Female":"1231–Overleden","1231":"1231","1264":"1264","1262":"1262","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1268":"1268","1453":"1453","1266":"1266","1243":"1243","about 1268":"circa 1268","about 1266":"circa 1266","about 1231":"circa 1231","about 1264":"circa 1264","about 1262":"circa 1262","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Willenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Willenhall, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1231–":"about 1231–Deceased","1227–Male":"1227–Deceased","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1262–Female":"1262–Deceased","1264–Male":"1264–Deceased","1266–Female":"1266–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1231–Female":"1231–Deceased","1231":"1231","1264":"1264","1262":"1262","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1268":"1268","1453":"1453","1266":"1266","1243":"1243","about 1268":"about 1268","about 1266":"about 1266","about 1231":"about 1231","about 1264":"about 1264","about 1262":"about 1262","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Willenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Willenhall, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clement","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alcide, Alphonse, Andre, Marcel, Armand, Cecile, Christophe, Gaston, Olivier, Aime.","English, Catalan, German, Flemish, and Dutch; French and Walloon (<b>Clément</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Clemens</i> meaning ‘merciful’ (genitive <i>Clementis</i>). This achieved popularity firstly through having been borne by an early Christian saint who was a disciple of Saint Paul, and later because it was selected as a symbolic name by a number of early popes. There has also been some confusion with the personal name <i>Clemence</i> (from Latin <i>Clementia</i>, meaning ‘mercy’, an abstract noun derived from the adjective; in part a masculine name from Latin <i>Clementius</i>, a later derivative of <i>Clemens</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Clemente  , and also their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Clem","meanings":["English (Somerset): from a short form of the personal name   Clement   or of the female form, <i>Clemence</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Klemm</b> and German or Dutch <b>Klem</b>: from a short form of the personal name   Klemens  ."]},{"name":"Clements","meanings":["English, Irish (Tyrone and Antrim), and Dutch: variant of   Clement  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Clementz   and Slovenian patronymic <b>Klemenc</b> (see   Klements  )."]},{"name":"Clemente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Elia, Manuel, Cesar, Fernando, Luis, Rafael, Alfredo, Andres, Armando, Gerardo.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Salvatore, Vito, Gino, Angelo, Nicola, Rocco, Enrico, Guido, Marco, Matteo.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese: from the personal name<i>Clemente</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Crimi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gaetano, Vita, Cosimo, Giuseppe, Luciano, Luigi, Sal, Tommaso.","Italian (Sicily): from an altered form of the medieval Greek personal name <i>Klēmēs</i>, from Latin <i>Clemens</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Chimenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Francesco, Filomena, Guido.","Italian (southern): variant of <b>Clementi</b> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clemon","meanings":["English: probably from a variant of the personal name   Clement  .","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McClymont  ."]},{"name":"Klehm","meanings":["North German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Klement</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clementson","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Clement   + <i>-son</i>. See also   Clements   and   Clemson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Klementsson</b> or <b>Clementsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Klement</i>,   Clement  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian <b>Clementsen</b> or <b>Klementsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Kelemen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Andras, Gabor, Geza, Imre, Laszlo, Tibor, Bela, Gyula, Istvan, Jozsef, Karoly, Leszlo.","Hungarian, Croatian, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Kelemen</i>, Hungarian form of   Clement  . The Hungarian surname is also common in Romania."]},{"name":"Climie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scots pet form of the personal name   Clement  ."]}]},{"name":"Alma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Relatively modern creation, of uncertain origin. It had a temporary vogue following the Battle of Alma (  1854 ), which is named from the river in the Crimea by which it took place; similarly, <i>Trafalgar</i> had occasionally been used as a girl's name earlier in the 19th century. Nevertheless, the historical event seems only to have increased the popularity of an existing, if rare, name. <i>Alma</i> is also the feminine form of the Latin adjective <i>almus</i> ‘nourishing, kind’ (compare the term <i>alma mater</i> ‘fostering mother’, denoting an educational establishment). The name was borne by  Alma Bennett  (  1889–1958 ), American vamp of the silent screen. In  Tennessee Williams's  play Summer and Smoke (  1948 ), a bearer of the name explains that it is ‘Spanish for soul’, but this seems to be no more than coincidental."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvent